  "prompt": "How do you sort a collection in Java?",
  "response": "To sort a collection in Java, we can use various approaches depending on the type of collection and the sorting requirements. Let's go through the most common methods:\n\n1. Sorting Lists (e.g., ArrayList, LinkedList):\n\nThe most common method to sort a List is by using the `Collections.sort()` method. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.Collections;\nimport java.util.List;\n\npublic class SortingExample {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        // Create a list of integers\n        List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();\n        numbers.add(5);\n        numbers.add(2);\n        numbers.add(8);\n        numbers.add(1);\n        numbers.add(9);\n\n        // Sort the list in natural order\n        Collections.sort(numbers);\n\n        // Print the sorted list\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted list: \" + numbers);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor custom objects, you need to implement the `Comparable` interface or provide a `Comparator`. Here's an example with a custom class:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.Collections;\nimport java.util.List;\n\nclass Person implements Comparable<Person> {\n    private String name;\n    private int age;\n\n    public Person(String name, int age) {\n        this.name = name;\n        this.age = age;\n    }\n\n    public String getName() {\n        return name;\n    }\n\n    public int getAge() {\n        return age;\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public int compareTo(Person other) {\n        // Sort by age in ascending order\n        return Integer.compare(this.age, other.age);\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public String toString() {\n        return \"Person{name='\" + name + \"', age=\" + age + \"}\";\n    }\n}\n\npublic class SortingExample {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<Person> people = new ArrayList<>();\n        people.add(new Person(\"Alice\", 30));\n        people.add(new Person(\"Bob\", 25));\n        people.add(new Person(\"Charlie\", 35));\n\n        // Sort the list using natural ordering (by age)\n        Collections.sort(people);\n\n        // Print the sorted list\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted list by age: \" + people);\n\n        // Sort using a custom Comparator (by name)\n        Collections.sort(people, (p1, p2) -> p1.getName().compareTo(p2.getName()));\n\n        // Print the sorted list\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted list by name: \" + people);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n2. Sorting Arrays:\n\nFor arrays, you can use the `Arrays.sort()` method:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Arrays;\n\npublic class SortingExample {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        int[] numbers = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9};\n\n        // Sort the array in natural order\n        Arrays.sort(numbers);\n\n        // Print the sorted array\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted array: \" + Arrays.toString(numbers));\n    }\n}\n```\n\n3. Sorting with Streams:\n\nJava 8 introduced the Stream API, which provides a more functional approach to sorting:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Arrays;\nimport java.util.List;\nimport java.util.stream.Collectors;\n\npublic class SortingExample {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(5, 2, 8, 1, 9);\n\n        // Sort the list using streams\n        List<Integer> sortedNumbers = numbers.stream()\n                .sorted()\n                .collect(Collectors.toList());\n\n        // Print the sorted list\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted list: \" + sortedNumbers);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThese are the main ways to sort collections in Java. The choice of method depends on the specific requirements of your application, such as the type of collection, the need for custom sorting, and whether you're working with streams or traditional collections.",
